<h1>Sacramento Choo Choo</h1>
<h2>HSR25-89 Timeline and Analysis</h2>
<img src="../assets/horiz-rr-track.png">
<h3>
<p><u>Overview</u></p>
<p> On June 1, 2026, the California High-Speed Rail Authority awarded a
$3.5 billion Track and Systems Construction Contract (HSR25-89) to
Kiewit, Stacy Witbeck, Herzog ('Kiewit'). </p>
<p> The only other Proposer (California High Speed Partners) was
disqualified early on and their bid was <i>never analyzed or evaluated</i>
by the Authority. </p>
<p> The disqualification decision was justified by the lack of
California Professional Engineer licensure by one member of the key
personnel proposed by CHSP, a requirement <i>not mandated by state law</i>
as the role in question did not involve engineering work. </p>
<p> The bidding process thereby devolved into <i>non-competitive
(single-source) procurement</i>. Apart from its dubious legality, this
arrangement demonstrates abysmal stewardship of public monies by the
Authority and its Board of Directors. </p>
After the protest filed by CHCP was rejected, CHCP were given <i>absolutely
no time</i> to rectify the issue. On the <i>very next business day
after the rejection</i>,
the Board of Directors authorized the execution of the award contract
to Kiewit. Previously, the Authority extended the due date for
proposals - <i>twice</i>. There is no reason why contract execution
could likewise not have been postponed.
<p> Given these irregularities, it is imperative that the HSR25-89
bidding process be thoroughly investigated, in its entirety, by
applicable state and Federal agencies. </p>
<p><u>Timeline</u></p>
<p> On November 25, 2025, the California High-Speed Rail Authority
(‚&#8364;&#732;Authority‚&#8364;&#8482;) issued a <a href="../docs/TSCC-Webpage-20260326.pdf">Request
for Proposals</a> (‚&#8364;&#732;RFP‚&#8364;&#8482;) from parties (‚&#8364;&#732;Proposers‚&#8364;&#8482;) interested
in submitting bids for the HSR25-89 Track and Systems Construction
Contract (‚&#8364;&#732;TSCC‚&#8364;&#8482;). &gt;On December 19, 2025, The Authority
organized a <a
 href="../docs/TSCC-Pre-Bid-Registration-List-12-19-25-A11Y.pdf">well-attended</a>
Pre-bid Conference and Small Business Workshop in connection with the
TSCC.</p>
<p>Concurrently with the RFP, the Authority also issued the initial
versions of its <a
 href="../docs/HSR25-89_AD0_TSCC_Instructions_to_Proposers-Clean.pdf">Instructions
to Proposers</a> (‚&#8364;&#732;ITP‚&#8364;&#8482;) and the <a
 href="../docs/HSR25-89_AD0_TSCC_Agreement-Clean.pdf">TSCC Agreement</a>
template (‚&#8364;&#732;Agreement‚&#8364;&#8482;). Over subsequent months, the Authority also
organized ten <a
 href="../2025-12-09_HSR25-89_Questions_and_Answers_Round_1.pdf">
Questions and Responses</a> ‚&#8364;&#339;rounds‚&#8364;&#157; for the benefit of the
Proposers, while simultaneously producing eight revisions
(‚&#8364;&#732;Addenda‚&#8364;&#8482;) of both the ITP and the Agreement template. </p>
<p> The ITP contains a detailed <a
 href="../HSR25-89_AD8_TSCC_Instructions_to_Proposers-Clean.pdf#page=25">Procurement
Schedule</a>, particularly the project submission Due Date, initially
set for <a
 href="../docs/HSR25-89_AD0_TSCC_Instructions_to_Proposers-Clean.pdf#page=26">March
2, 2026</a>, but subsequently pushed back to <a
 href="../docs/HSR25-89_AD2_TSCC_Instructions_to_Proposers-Clean.pdf#page=24">March
23, 2026</a>, <a
 href="../docs/HSR25-89_AD5_TSCC_Instructions_to_Proposers-Clean.pdf#page=25">April
1, 2026</a> and finally <a
 href="../docs/HSR25-89_AD7_TSCC_Instructions_to_Proposers-Clean.pdf#page=25">April
9, 2026</a>.</p>
<p>The Agreement outlines the <a
 href="../HSR25-89_AD8_TSCC_Agreement-Clean.pdf#page=68">licensure
requirements</a>, specifically the California Professional Engineer
license, for key personnel. Therein, the Authority also asserts its
prerogative to <a href="../docs/HSR25-89-TSCC_Agreement.pdf#page=27">
&gt;waive immaterialities and other deficiencies </a> found in
documents submitted by Proposers. </p>
<p class="MsoNormal"> <span style="font-size: 16pt; line-height: 115%;">
Over subsequent months, the Authority organized 10 <a
 href="../2025-12-09_HSR25-89_Questions_and_Answers_Round_1.pdf"> <span
 style="font-size: 16pt; line-height: 115%;">question-and-answer </span></a><span
 style="font-size: 16pt; line-height: 115%;"> ‚&#8364;&#339;rounds‚&#8364;&#157; for the
benefit of the Proposers, while simultaneously producing 8 revisions
(‚&#8364;&#732;Addenda‚&#8364;&#8482;) of both the ITP and the Agreement template. </span></span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal"> <span style="font-size: 16pt; line-height: 115%;">
On April 29, 2026, the Authority issued its <a
 href="../NOPA-TSCC-4-29-26-A11Y.pdf"> <span
 style="font-size: 16pt; line-height: 115%;">Notice of Proposed Award </span></a><span
 style="font-size: 16pt; line-height: 115%;"> (‚&#8364;&#732;NOPA‚&#8364;&#8482;), publicly
revealing the identities of the two bidders for the HSR25-89 contract
for the first time: </span></span></p>
<p class="MsoListParagraphCxSpFirst" style="text-indent: -0.25in;"><!--[if !supportLists]-->
<span style="font-size: 16pt; line-height: 115%;" lang="PL"> <span
 style="">
-<span
 style="font-family: &quot;Times New Roman&quot;; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; font-weight: normal; font-size: 7pt; line-height: normal; font-size-adjust: none; font-stretch: normal;">
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<!--[endif]--> <span
 style="font-size: 16pt; line-height: 115%;" lang="PL">Kiewit, Stacy
Witbeck, Herzog (‚&#8364;&#732;Kiewit‚&#8364;&#8482;) </span></span></span></span></p>
<p class="MsoListParagraphCxSpLast" style="text-indent: -0.25in;"><!--[if !supportLists]-->
<span style="font-size: 16pt; line-height: 115%;"> <span style=""> -<span
 style="font-family: &quot;Times New Roman&quot;; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; font-weight: normal; font-size: 7pt; line-height: normal; font-size-adjust: none; font-stretch: normal;">
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<!--[endif]--> <span
 style="font-size: 16pt; line-height: 115%;"> California High Speed
Partners (‚&#8364;&#732;CHSP‚&#8364;&#8482;) </span></span></span></span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal"> <span style="font-size: 16pt; line-height: 115%;">
The Kiewit proposal was duly evaluated and scored.<span style=""> The
CHSP proposal, however, was not: instead of a score, a cryptic
‚&#8364;&#339;N/A‚&#8364;&#157; is provided, with absolutely no information as to its
meaning. </span></span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal"> <span style="font-size: 16pt; line-height: 115%;">
It turns out that the Authority concluded that CHSP was <a
 href="https://youtu.be/zZmCt1chOy8?t=3436"> <span
 style="font-size: 16pt; line-height: 115%;">non-responsive </span></a><span
 style="font-size: 16pt; line-height: 115%;"> and did not meet all of
the requirements outlined in the FRP.<span style=""> Specifically, the
individual being put forth as the Design Oversight Manager for the
project <a href="https://youtu.be/zZmCt1chOy8?t=4590"> <span
 style="font-size: 16pt; line-height: 115%;">lacked a valid California
Professional Engineer license </span></a><span
 style="font-size: 16pt; line-height: 115%;">. </span></span></span></span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal"> <span style="font-size: 16pt; line-height: 115%;">
CHCP filed a Protest with the Authority on May 5, 2026, which was <a
 href="https://youtu.be/zZmCt1chOy8?t=3459"> <span
 style="font-size: 16pt; line-height: 115%;">dismissed on May 29, 2026 </span></a><span
 style="font-size: 16pt; line-height: 115%;"> by the Authority‚&#8364;&#8482;s <a
 href="https://youtu.be/zZmCt1chOy8?t=4590"> <span
 style="font-size: 16pt; line-height: 115%;">‚&#8364;&#339;independent protest
official‚&#8364;&#157; </span></a>.<span style=""> After their Protest was
rejected, CHCP were given no opportunity at all to rectify the
deficiency of their Proposal.<span style=""> The rejection of the
Protest purportedly allowed the <span
 style="font-size: 16pt; line-height: 115%;"> Authority to <a
 href="https://youtu.be/zZmCt1chOy8?t=3571"> <span
 style="font-size: 16pt; line-height: 115%;">proceed to contract
execution </span></a>, which was done on the very next business day.<span
 style="font-size: 16pt; line-height: 115%;"> <span style=""> On June
1, 2026, the Board of Directors, after some discussion, voted
unanimously to award the HSR25-89 contract to Kiewit.<span style=""> </span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal"> <span style="font-size: 16pt; line-height: 115%;">
Some of the Board members did express reservations about <a
 href="https://youtu.be/zZmCt1chOy8?t=3591"> <span
 style="font-size: 16pt; line-height: 115%;">relying on a single bidder
</span></a>,<span style="font-size: 16pt; line-height: 115%;">
frustration with not being able to compare the <a
 href="https://youtu.be/zZmCt1chOy8?t=3670"> <span
 style="font-size: 16pt; line-height: 115%;">pricing </span></a><span
 style="font-size: 16pt; line-height: 115%;"> put forth by both
Proposers, and belief that the non-compliance <a
 href="https://youtu.be/zZmCt1chOy8?t=4911"> <span
 style="font-size: 16pt; line-height: 115%;">easily curable </span></a><span
 style="font-size: 16pt; line-height: 115%;"> .<span style=""> But none
of this affected the final vote. </span></span></span></span></span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="font-size: 16pt; line-height: 115%;"><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: center;" align="center"> <u> <span
 style="font-size: 16pt; line-height: 115%;">Analysis </span></u><span
 style="font-size: 16pt; line-height: 115%;"> </span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="font-size: 16pt; line-height: 115%;"><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal"> <span style="font-size: 16pt; line-height: 115%;">
The Authority‚&#8364;&#8482;s disqualification of one of the bidders resulted in a <i>
non-competitive (sole-source) procurement </i> valued at $3.5 billion
‚&#8364;&#8220; and probably much more down the road, given the virtual certainty
of future change orders.<span style=""> At the very least, the Board of
Directors demonstrated an abysmal stewardship of public resources.<span
 style=""> A politically independent analysis of the <i>entirety</i>
of the bidding process, including the circumstances and reasoning for
excluding CHSP from it, must be conducted by appropriate state and
Federal agencies. </span></span></span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="font-size: 16pt; line-height: 115%;"><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal"> <span style="font-size: 16pt; line-height: 115%;">
In the meantime, it would be instructive to try and unpack the
licensure non-compliance that disqualified CHSP from the bidding
process. </span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="font-size: 16pt; line-height: 115%;"><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal"> <span style="font-size: 16pt; line-height: 115%;">
We begin with Section 5 of the proposed TSCC Agreement, which
stipulates the need for appropriate accreditation acceptable to the
State of California. </span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal"> <span style=""> <v:shapetype id="_x0000_t75"
 coordsize="21600,21600" o:spt="75" o:preferrelative="t"
 path="m@4@5l@4@11@9@11@9@5xe" filled="f" stroked="f"> <v:stroke
 joinstyle="miter"> <v:formulas> <v:f
 eqn="if lineDrawn pixelLineWidth 0"> <v:f eqn="sum @0 1 0"> <v:f
 eqn="sum 0 0 @1"> <v:f eqn="prod @2 1 2"> <v:f
 eqn="prod @3 21600 pixelWidth"> <v:f eqn="prod @3 21600 pixelHeight">
<v:f eqn="sum @0 0 1"> <v:f eqn="prod @6 1 2"> <v:f
 eqn="prod @7 21600 pixelWidth"> <v:f eqn="sum @8 21600 0"> <v:f
 eqn="prod @7 21600 pixelHeight"> <v:f eqn="sum @10 21600 0"> </v:f> <v:path
 o:extrusionok="f" gradientshapeok="t" o:connecttype="rect"> <o:lock
 v:ext="edit" aspectratio="t"> </o:lock><v:shape id="_x0000_i1027"
 type="#_x0000_t75"
 style="width: 468.5pt; height: 192pt; visibility: visible;"> <v:imagedata
 src="analysis_image001.png" o:title=""> </v:imagedata><span
 style="font-size: 16pt; line-height: 115%;"> </span></v:shape></v:path></v:f></v:f></v:f></v:f></v:f></v:f></v:f></v:f></v:f></v:f></v:f></v:formulas></v:stroke></v:shapetype></span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal"> <span style="font-size: 16pt; line-height: 115%;">
Note that the <i>origin</i> and <i>type</i> of permissible
accreditations are <i>not</i> specified. </span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="font-size: 16pt; line-height: 115%;"><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal"> <span style="font-size: 16pt; line-height: 115%;">
Next, we shall look at Schedule 17, which outlines the responsibilities
of key individuals overseeing the project.<span style=""> Specifically,
we are interested in the role of the Design Oversight Manager. </span></span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal"> <span style=""> <v:shape id="Picture_x0020_2"
 o:spid="_x0000_i1026" type="#_x0000_t75"
 style="width: 467.5pt; height: 79.5pt; visibility: visible;"> <v:imagedata
 src="analysis_image002.png" o:title="" croptop="1214f"> </v:imagedata><span
 style="font-size: 16pt; line-height: 115%;"> </span></v:shape></span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal"> <span style="font-size: 16pt; line-height: 115%;">
Notably, the Design Oversight Manager is <i>not</i> required to
perform engineering work or supervise those who do.<span style=""> This
is a liaison position and involves ‚&#8364;&#339;interfacing‚&#8364;&#157; with some of the
other stakeholders in the project. </span></span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="font-size: 16pt; line-height: 115%;"><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal"> <span style="font-size: 16pt; line-height: 115%;">
The non-engineering nature of the Design Oversight Manager role is
important. </span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal"> <span style=""> <v:shape id="Picture_x0020_1"
 o:spid="_x0000_i1025" type="#_x0000_t75"
 style="width: 468.5pt; height: 82pt; visibility: visible;"> <v:imagedata
 src="analysis_image003.png" o:title=""> </v:imagedata><span
 style="font-size: 16pt; line-height: 115%;"> </span></v:shape></span></p>
</h3>
